MCQ 21: C

Specific latent heat of vaporisation is the amount of energy to change a substance from liquid phase to gaseous phase without a change in temperature. Therefore, it is more difficult to have a phase change at 20 0C compared to that at 100 0C as the molecules in the liquid phase at 20 0C are more tightly bound to one another. The average energy of the molecules at 20 oC is less than that at 100 oC, so more energy needs to be provided to separate them against their mutual attraction.


MCQ 22: A

Short explanation:

During expansion at constant temperature, the work done on the gas is negative as the gas expands. Therefore, the work done by the gas is positive.


Detailed explanation:

For an ideal gas,

total internal energy = total KE of all molecules

= average KE per molecule  total no. of molecules

Hence, if the temperature T stays constant during the expansion,

the internal energy U stays constant.


By the First Law of Thermodynamics,


Since ∆U = 0，


Since the gas expands, the work done on the gas, W < 0.


 The gas absorbs heat from its surroundings during the expansion, and uses this heat to do work on its surroundings so that there is no increase in its internal energy.


B cannot be the answer because the gas still needs to do work on the surrounding atmosphere to expand its volume, even if no work needs to be done against intermolecular forces.


C is not the answer because the gas needs to expand against an external atmosphere. C would be the answer if no external atmospheric pressure is present, in which case the ideal gas is able to expand freely without any opposition (free expansion).


D. While it is true that the external pressure decreases during the expansion, it is also true that the gas still needs to do work against this pressure. Hence, the work done by the gas is still positive.

MCQ 24: D

A is incorrect: The shape of the graph of the variation of electric potential with position between two oppositely charged particles (left positive, right negative) is as follows:

It can be seen that the potential is zero at only one point between the particles, and not everywhere. Hence, A is not the answer.


B is incorrect: The shape of the graph of the variation of electric field strength with position between two oppositely charged particles (left positive, right negative) is as follows:

It can be seen that the electric field E is positive everywhere between the two charges. This implies that the direction of the electric field is constant, always pointing towards the right (in the positive direction).

Hence, answer B is wrong because the electric field strength is always greater than zero at all points between the two charges.


C is incorrect: The shape of the graph of the variation of electric potential with position between two similarly charged particles (both positive) is as follows:


It can be seen that the electric potential V is positive everywhere between the two charges. This is because the electric potentials contributed by the two charges are both positive at any point between the charges.

Hence, answer C is wrong because the electric potential is always greater than zero at all points between the two charges.


D is correct: The shape of the graph of the variation of electric field strength with position between two similarly charged particles (both positive) is as follows:


It can be seen that the electric field is positive at positions nearer to the left positive charge, which implies that the direction of the field at these positions is to the right, because the electric field due to the left charge is greater in magnitude than the field due to the right charge.

Similarly,

the electric field is negative at positions nearer to the right positive charge, which implies that the direction of the field at these positions is to the left, because the electric field due to the right charge is greater in magnitude than the field due to the left charge.

Hence, there will be a point between the two charges where the net electric field is zero, because the separate fields contributed by the two charges are equal in magnitude but opposite in direction at this point.

Hence, D is the correct answer.

MCQ 37: A


A is correct: The presence of impurities in a semiconductor increases the conductivity which mean decreases the resistance.

B is wrong: The energy gap between the valence and conduction bands in semiconductors is around 1 eV, which is considered “small”.

C is wrong: At low temperatures near 0 K, almost all of the electrons are bound in the covalent bonds in semiconductors, so that there is little movement of electrons even when a p.d. is present across the material. In terms of the energy level diagram, this means that few electrons are found in the conduction band.

D is wrong: When a p.d. is applied across an intrinsic semiconductor, any electron that has broken free from its covalent bond will experience an electric force towards the end of the material with a higher potential (more positive end), while the resulting vacancy (“hole”) will move in the direction of the electric field towards the end with lower potential (more negative end).

(c)

[1] for any 3 of the following points:


At higher temperatures, an electron may gain enough energy to move from the valence band to the conduction band leaving behind a vacant site known as the hole, in the otherwise filled valence band.


This hole acts as a positive charge carrier as a free electron from a nearby site can then move into the hole.


Whenever an electron does so, it creates a new hole at the site it abandoned. The net effect will be viewed as the hole moving in opposite direction to the movement of the electron.


These movements of holes and electrons give rise to a current in the same direction when an external electric field is applied. Electrons conduct in the conduction band, while holes conduct in the valence band.

6 (a) (i) The principle of superposition states that when 2 or more waves of the same kind exist simultaneously at a point, the resultant displacement of the waves at that point in time and space is the vector sum of the displacements due to each wave acting independently. [1]



(ii) When 2 waves of same phase meet, they superpose with each other to give a resultant wave of larger amplitude. This is known as constructive interference. [1]

When 2 waves of opposite phase meet, they superpose with each other to give a resultant wave of smaller amplitude. This is known as destructive interference. [1]
